issue.title: Sidebar folders order depends on their page order property
issue.body:
### What version of `starlight` are you using?

0.14.0

### What version of `astro` are you using?

3.6.4

### What package manager are you using?

pnpm

### What operating system are you using?

Mac

### What browser are you using?

Chrome

### Describe the Bug

As discussed on Discord,
```
Structure:
 - docs/
    - category/
      - folder-1/
        - page-1.md
        - page-2.md
      - folder-2/
        - page-1.md
        - page-2.md
```

If I give my folder-1/page-1.md an order property of 10, and my folder-2/page-1.md an order property of 5, I end-up with my folder-2 being ranked above folder-1 in my sidebar.

Said differently, autogenerated folders are sorted according to the order of the first page in the directory.

In the stackblitz example linked below, in the fruits directory, the banana subdirectory comes before the apples subdirectory because it has a page with order 1, when apples has a page with order 5.

### Link to Minimal Reproducible Example

https://stackblitz.com/edit/github-dssfwv?file=src%2Fcontent%2Fdocs%2Ffruits%2Fbananas%2Flatundan.md

### Participation

- [X] I am willing to submit a pull request for this issue.

comment.body:
> Nuxt Content has [a very nice way](https://content.nuxt.com/usage/content-directory#ordering) of supporting custom ordering, by allowing numeric prefixes in the filename, which it then ignores when generating the slug/ID.

Since Starlight [0.35.0](https://github.com/withastro/starlight/releases/tag/%40astrojs%2Fstarlight%400.35.0) added the [`generateId()`](https://starlight.astro.build/reference/configuration/#generateid) callback function which enables customization of how URLs from filenames (`entry`) are transformed, you can now achieve the same behavior in Starlight (but without i18n unfortunately).

I wrote a blog post of how to do exactly that if anyone is still interested in such a setup: https://blog.trueberryless.org/blog/starlight-autogenerate-whole-sidebar/

pull_request.body:
This pull request refactors and improves the theme color caching mechanism in the `home_interface.py` file. The main changes focus on ensuring the theme color is only cached and reused when the background image has not changed, by tracking the image's modification time. This prevents outdated theme colors from being used if the background image is updated.

**Theme color caching improvements:**

* Added `_can_use_cached_theme_color` and `_update_theme_color_cache` methods to check whether the cached theme color is still valid based on the background image path and its modification time, and to update the cache accordingly. Also added `_clear_theme_color_cache` to force cache clearing when needed.
* Updated all relevant logic (`_get_theme_color`, `_update_start_button_style_from_banner`) to use the new cache validation methods instead of only checking the image path. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-f9c175af52ab8303d68d9e0c072f15817fd182105bab61fe482d60430b0e361eL568-R575) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-f9c175af52ab8303d68d9e0c072f15817fd182105bab61fe482d60430b0e361eL589-R594) [[3]](diffhunk://#diff-f9c175af52ab8303d68d9e0c072f15817fd182105bab61fe482d60430b0e361eL600-R603)
* Now tracks the modification time of the cached banner image (`_cached_banner_mtime`) to ensure the cache is invalidated if the image changes.

**Bug fixes and reliability:**

* Ensured the theme color cache is cleared before reloading the banner, preventing stale theme colors after a background change.
